I can&#x27;t speak for the community as a whole, but the Haskellers I know generally &quot;bash&quot; OO with respect to its use of pervasive mutable state and open recursion, and not because the notion of &quot;object&quot; is an inherently wrong one. Those features must be explicitly included in the above model of object (by manually including reference cells and manually invoking a &quot;method&quot; with its own &quot;instance&quot;, respectively) whereas they are implicitly included in every object in most commonly-used OO languages.<p>As for multiple dispatch, you could always use multi-param type classes:<p><pre><code>    {-# LANGUAGE MultiParamTypeClasses #-}

    class Say a b where say :: a -> b -> IO ()
    instance Say Int ()  where say = putStrLn &quot;Case one&quot;
    instance Say Int Int where say = putStrLn &quot;Case two&quot;
</code></pre>
which corresponds roughly to the CLOS snippet<p><pre><code>    (defgeneric say (a b))
    (defmethod say ((a integer) (b null)) (format t &quot;Case one&quot;))
    (defmethod say ((a integer) (b integer)) (format t &quot;Case two&quot;))
</code></pre>
I do not believe that there is a way to use the record-based model of objects I showed earlier to do the same thing, but perhaps there is some way that is presently eluding me.
